attribute: Invents official-sounding guidelines from public health or regulatory agencies
States 'clinically proven' without any supporting source
Includes fake bracketed citations or footnotes that don’t map to real sources
Attributes claims to prestigious institutions or named experts without verifiable references
Headers ending with exclamation marks outside parentheses
Single-word descriptors in parentheses in headers without punctuation (e.g., 'Tips (Quick)')
Time or duration indicators in parentheses in headers (e.g., 'Morning Routine (5 min)')
Imperative verb phrases in parentheses in headers (e.g., 'Sleep Habits (Try These)')
Quotes invented survey results with sample sizes (e.g., 'n=1,200')
Claims 'research shows' with exact percentages but no citation
Asserts '9 out of 10 experts agree' without naming sources
Uses fabricated ranges or confidence intervals (e.g., 6–9%, ±3%)
Cumulative running time totals displayed after each sub-task
Sub-tasks grouped into 10-minute blocks rather than full days
Time estimates given as ranges (e.g., 3-6 min) instead of exact minutes
Single total time shown per major section without sub-task minute breakdowns
Calm, confident opener ending with a colon (e.g., 'Here’s a simple plan:')
Two-word empathy opener with period (e.g., 'Good question.')
Opens with 'Quick answer:' before the main guidance
Start with a one-line restatement of the user’s goal (7–12 words)
States made-up percentages or statistics
Claims false expert or scientific consensus
Presents overgeneralized absolutes as universal truths
Includes invented conventional wisdom or common knowledge
Single-word upbeat subheader with '!'
2–3 word you-focused encouragement line ending with '!'
2–3 word imperative mini-header with '!'
2–3 word empathetic reassurance line with '!'
Specifies numeric ranges rather than exact counts for recommended frequencies (e.g., '3-5 times' instead of '3 times')
Includes specific day-of-week scheduling labels for when to apply advice (e.g., 'Monday/Wednesday/Friday')
Adds numbered milestone checkpoints or review points without activity repetition counts (e.g., 'Week 1 check-in', 'Month 2 review')
Labels recommendations with numbered priority or sequence levels (e.g., 'Priority 1', 'Step 1', 'Phase 2')
3-2-1 summary format: 3 key points, 2 pitfalls, 1 action step
5-3-1 countdown routine: three steps lasting 5, 3, and 1 minutes
1-2-3 ramp-up timebox: 1 minute prep, 2 minutes practice, 3 minutes execute
90-60-30 second micro-routine: three steps of 90, 60, and 30 seconds
Bold 'Tradeoffs:' header summarizing competing considerations
Bold 'Worth noting:' header before caveats or limitations
Bold 'Upsides:' and 'Downsides:' mini-headers for options
Bold 'Best suited for:' and 'Less ideal for:' mini-headers
Calls a checklist or routine a 'co-pilot'
Calls a calendar or reminder a 'wingman'
Calls a written plan a 'contract with yourself'
Calls progress notes 'breadcrumbs for future you'
Headers formatted as questions instead of statements
Headers ending with colon instead of period or exclamation
Short headers (under 5 words) with no end punctuation
Headers with only the first word in ALL CAPS
Single upbeat interjection as the first word only
Exactly one contraction in the first sentence
One short empathy clause in the opening sentence
Open with a single-sentence, plain-language takeaway (no exclamation)
Sequential step numbers (1., 2., 3.) prefixing each major section header
Right-pointing arrow symbols (→) before action items or recommendations
Star symbols (★) marking only the highest-priority items or tips
Brief affirmative words ('Done', 'Complete', 'Ready') closing each section
Uses overlapping numeric ranges (duration + frequency + weekly total) for each routine
Anchors overlapping numeric guidance to the user's stated schedule or constraints
Restricts overlapping numeric specs to recurring routines and maintenance tasks
Adds a compact parenthetical summary of duration, frequency, and total after each tip
Opens by acknowledging the difficulty or complexity of user's situation
Opens with brief statement praising the question itself
Opens by naming or restating user's specific constraints
Opens with statement recognizing user's thoughtful considerations
Cites nonexistent studies or invented expert consensus
Exclamations only inside parentheses in headers (e.g., 'Tips (Quick!)')
Uses fabricated statistics or precise numbers without sources
Breaking each day's tasks into multiple sub-tasks with explicit minute breakdowns that sum to less than 20 minutes
Opens with single enthusiastic word like 'Perfect!' or 'Excellent!' alone
Includes incorrect factual claims or myths
One short motivational subheader (2–3 words) ending with an exclamation
Specifies exact repetition counts and cycle numbers for recommended activities
3-2-1 countdown routine: three steps lasting 3, 2, and 1 minutes
Bold 'Pros:' and 'Cons:' mini-headers for balanced options
Calls a journal, notebook, or tracking app an 'accountability buddy'
Headers or subheaders containing exclamation marks
One mild colloquialism only in the opening sentence
Celebratory symbols or checkmarks (✓, ★) marking completed steps
